1. Download the Installer
1.	Open your browser and navigate to the Official AWS CLI Download Page.
2.	Click on the Windows (64-bit) installer.
3.	This will download the file: AWSCLIV2.msi.
2. Install the CLI
1.	Double-click the AWSCLIV2.msi file.
2.	Follow the installation wizard:
o	Click Next.
o	Accept the terms and click Install.
o	Click Finish.
Note: Windows automatically adds the AWS CLI to your system PATH, so you don't need to configure environment variables manually.
3. Verify Installation
Open Command Prompt or PowerShell and run the following command to ensure the CLI is recognized:
Bash
aws --version
Example Output: aws-cli/2.15.0 Python/3.11 Windows/10 exe/AMD64 If you see this, the installation was successful! ✅
4. Configure Your Credentials
To connect the CLI to your specific AWS account, run the configuration command:
Bash
aws configure
You will be prompted to enter four pieces of information. If you don't have these yet, you can find them in the IAM Console under your user's "Security Credentials."
Prompt	Example Value
AWS Access Key ID	AKIAxxxxxxxxxxxx
AWS Secret Access Key	xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
Default region name	ap-south-1 (or your preferred region)
Default output format	json

5. Credential Storage Location
Once configured, AWS stores your settings in a hidden folder in your User directory. You can find them here:
•	Credentials: C:\Users\YourUsername\.aws\credentials
•	Config: C:\Users\YourUsername\.aws\config
⚠️ Security Warning: Never share or commit your .aws/credentials file to version control.
________________________________________
6. Test the Connection
Verify that the CLI can communicate with your AWS account by listing your S3 buckets:
Bash
aws s3 ls
If you have buckets, they will be listed. If you have no buckets yet, it will simply return a blank line (which still means it's working!).

